  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>No model is complete. For banks, traditional DCFs have specific blind spots.</p>

  <h3>The "Net Cash" Illusion</h3>
  <p>In our model, Net Cash (Cash + Short-Term Investments - Total Debt) adds over $100 billion to the equity value. However, for a bank, cash and short-term investments are largely held against deposit liabilities. They aren't "excess cash" that can be distributed to shareholders. This is why financial institutions are typically valued using Dividend Discount Models (DDM) or Residual Income models, which better account for regulatory capital requirements.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Higher Interest Rates:</strong> If rates stay higher for longer, BK earns more on its massive cash balances and securities portfolio (Net Interest Income).</li>
    <li><strong>Market Appreciation:</strong> As equity markets rise, BK's Assets Under Custody and Administration (AUC/A) naturally grow, lifting fee revenue without requiring extra work.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Deposit Flight:</strong> If clients move uninvested cash to higher-yielding alternatives, BK loses a cheap source of funding.</li>
    <li><strong>Fee Compression:</strong> The asset management and custody industries face relentless pressure to lower fees, which could erode margins over time.</li>
  </ul>

